JavaScript Foundations (Resume Form Basics)

üéì Theory Learned
1. Variables & Data Types (let, const)
Definition: Variables store data values.
let ‚Üí block-scoped, can be reassigned.
const ‚Üí block-scoped, cannot be reassigned.
Industry Use:
Store API keys, user session tokens, or global state in a web app.
Example: const API_KEY = "123xyz";
Creative Use:
A mood tracker app where each day‚Äôs mood is stored in a variable.
Example: let todayMood = "productive";


2. Conditionals & Loops
Conditionals: if, else if, else, switch ‚Üí used to check logical conditions.
Loops: for, while, do...while ‚Üí repeat code multiple times.
Industry Use:
Form Validation ‚Üí checking if the email contains @.
Dashboard Updates ‚Üí running checks on data repeatedly.
Creative Use:
A study reminder app that runs a loop to check system time and triggers an alert at study hours.


üìù Assignments Completed
Pass/Fail Checker

 let marks = 55;
if (marks >= 40) {
  console.log("Pass ‚úÖ");
} else {
  console.log("Fail ‚ùå");
}


First 10 Even Numbers

 for (let i = 1; i <= 10; i++) {
  console.log(i * 2);
}



üèóÔ∏è Project Task ‚Äì Resume Form
Features Implemented:
Fields: Name, Email, Skills
Validation:
Email must contain @
Skills cannot be empty


Sample Code:
<form id="resumeForm">
  <label>Name:</label>
  <input type="text" id="name" required><br><br>

  <label>Email:</label>
  <input type="text" id="email" required><br><br>

  <label>Skills:</label>
  <input type="text" id="skills" required><br><br>

  <button type="submit">Submit</button>
</form>

<script>
  document.getElementById("resumeForm").addEventListener("submit", function(event) {
    let email = document.getElementById("email").value;
    let skills = document.getElementById("skills").value;

    if (!email.includes("@")) {
      alert("Invalid email: must include @");
      event.preventDefault();
    }

    if (skills.trim() === "") {
      alert("Skills field cannot be empty");
      event.preventDefault();
    }
  });
</script>

